@node Frame sizing and positioning
@section Frame sizing and positioning

@findex frame-extras-maximize-frame
@findex frame-extras-left-half
@findex frame-extras-right-half
The command @code{frame-extras-maximize-frame} maximizes the current frame to fill the screen. It works by clearing any fullscreen state and then setting the @code{fullscreen} frame parameter to @code{'maximized}. After a brief delay (to allow the window manager to finish resizing), it records the frame width in @code{frame-extras-maximized-frame-width} for use by the half-screen commands.

The command @code{frame-extras-left-half} resizes the frame to occupy the left half of the screen. It first calls @code{frame-extras-maximize-frame} to determine the full screen width, then sets the frame width to half of @code{frame-extras-maximized-frame-width}. The frame remains anchored at the left edge of the screen.

The command @code{frame-extras-right-half} resizes the frame to the right half. It calls @code{frame-extras-left-half} to set the correct width, then repositions the frame so that its left edge aligns with the screen midpoint. Together, @code{frame-extras-left-half} and @code{frame-extras-right-half} provide a quick way to set up a side-by-side layout.

@node Restoration utilities
@section Restoration utilities

@findex frame-extras-restore-window-divider
@findex frame-extras-restore-focus
The command @code{frame-extras-restore-window-divider} resets the @code{window-divider} face to its default attributes using @code{custom-set-faces}. This is useful if the divider has been made invisible by a theme or customization and you want to restore its visibility.

The command @code{frame-extras-restore-focus} uses AppleScript (via @code{do-applescript}) to bring the Emacs application to the foreground and give it input focus on macOS@. This is helpful after an external process has stolen focus, for example after running a shell command that opens another application.

@node Functions
@chapter Functions

@vindex frame-extras-maximized-frame-width
The variable @code{frame-extras-maximized-frame-width} stores the width (in columns) of the frame after maximization. It defaults to @code{244} but is updated dynamically each time @code{frame-extras-maximize-frame} is called (@ref{Frame sizing and positioning}). The half-screen commands use this value to calculate the correct width for a half-width frame.

